ero], fun i hi ↦ ?_⟩\n      simp only [centerMass, sum_const, nsmul_eq_mul, mul_inv_rev, inv_inv, ← smul_sum, ← mul_smul,\n        mul_right_comm, ne_eq, Nat.cast_eq_zero, hs.nonempty.card_ne_zero, not_false_eq_true,\n        mul_inv_cancel₀, one_mul]\n      sorry\n```\n\nLooking at the proof, the strategy for the `mp` (forward) direction is:\n1. Assume existence of `z` and `c` satisfying the line map condition.\n2. Use `by_cases` to split into two cases:\n   - Case 1: `∀ i ∈ s, c i = 1`\n   - Case 2: `¬ (∀ i ∈ s, c i = 1)` (i.e., there exists some `j ∈ s` such that `c j ≠ 1`)\n\nIn Case 1, we need to construct weights `w` such that:\n- `∀ i ∈ s, 0 ≤ w i`\n- `∑ i ∈ s, w i = 1`\n- `∀ i ∈ s, (s \\ {i}).centerMass w x = y i`\n\nAs we saw earlier, if `c i = 1` for all `i ∈ s`, then `x i = y i` for all `i ∈ s`. So we need to construct `w` such that `centerMass w x = x i` for all `i ∈ s`.\n\nThe code proposes `w = fun _ ↦ (#s)⁻¹`. Let's check:\n- `∀ i ∈ s, 0 ≤ w i`: `1 / |s| ≥ 0` since `|s| ≥ 1`. This is true.\n- `∑ i ∈ s, w i = 1`: `∑ i ∈ s, 1 / |s| = |s| * (1 / |s|) = 1`. This is true.\n- `∀ i ∈ s, (s \\ {i}).centerMass w x = y i`: We need `centerMass w x = x i` for all `i ∈ s`.\n\nCompute `centerMass w x`:\n`∑ j ∈ s, w j • x j = ∑ j ∈ s, (1 / |s|) • x j = (∑ j ∈ s, x j) / |s|`\n\nSo we need `(∑ j ∈ s, x j) / |s| = x i` for all `i ∈ s`. This implies that all `x i` must be equal to the average `x` value. This only holds if all `x i` are equal.\n\nSo the strategy for Case 1 is incorrect. We need a different construction for `w`.\n\nLet's think differently. If `c i = 1` for all `i ∈ s`, then `x i = y i` for all `i ∈ s`. So we need to show that there exist weights `w` such that `∑ i ∈ s, w i = 1`, `∀ i ∈ s, w i ≥ 0`, and `(s \\ {i}).centerMass w x = x i` for all `i ∈ s`.\n\nOne simple solution is to choose `w i = 1` for some specific `j ∈ s` and `0` for all others. Let's try this.\n\nSuppose we pick `j ∈ s` and set `w j = 1` and `w i = 0` for all `i ≠ j`. Then:\n1. `∑ i ∈ s