      "\n  sorry\n```\n\nIn the case where all `c i = 1`, we need to show that `(s \\ {i}).centerMass w x = y i`. After simplifying, we need to show that `(↑(s \\ {i}).card)⁻¹ • ∑ x_1 ∈ s \\ {i}, x x_1 = y i`. \n\nSince `z = y i` for all `i ∈ s` (because `c i = 1`), we need to show that the center of mass of the set `s \\ {i}` with the weight function `w j = 1 / |s|` is `y i`. \n\nThe center of mass is given by `(1 / |s|) • ∑ x_j ∈ s \\ {i}, x_j`. Since `z = y i`, we need to show that `(1 / |s|) • ∑ x_j ∈ s \\ {i}, x_j = y i`. \n\nBut how do we know that `(1 / |s|) • ∑ x_j ∈ s \\ {i}, x_j = y i`? \n\nFrom `hy i hi`, we know that `y i ∈ convexHull 𝕜 (x '' (s \\ {i}))`. The definition of convex hull means that `y i` is a convex combination of points in `x '' (s \\ {i})`. So there exist weights `λ j` for `j ∈ s \\ {i}` such that `∑ λ j = 1` and `y i = ∑ λ j • x j`. \n\nHowever, we need to show that `(1 / |s|) • ∑ x_j ∈ s \\ {i}, x_j = y i`. This is not generally true. For example, if `s = {1, 2, 3}` and `i = 1`, then `s \\ {i} = {2, 3}`. The center of mass would be `(1/3) • (x 2 + x 3)`. But `y 1` could be something else.\n\nWait, there's a contradiction in the assumptions. If `c i = 1` for all `i ∈ s`, then `lineMap (y i) (x i) 1 = y i` must equal `z`. So `z = y i` for all `i ∈ s`. \n\nBut then, `hy i hi` says `y i ∈ convexHull 𝕜 (x '' (s \\ {i}))`. If `z = y i`, then `y i` is in the convex hull of `x '' (s \\ {i})`. But `y i` is not in the set `x '' (s \\ {i})` unless `i ∈ s \\ {i}`, which is false. \n\nSo this case is impossible. The assumption that `c i = 1` for all `i ∈ s` leads to a contradiction. \n\nLet's prove this contradiction formally:\n\n```tactics\nhave h1 := hy i hi\nsimp [hc i hi] at h1\n```\n\nWait, `hy i hi` is `y i ∈ convexHull 𝕜 (x '' (s \\ {i}))`. The definition of convex hull is `∑ j ∈ s \\ {i}, λ j • x j` where `∑ j ∈ s \\ {i}, λ j = 1` and `λ j ≥ 0`. \n\nBut `lineMap (y i) (x i) (c i) = z` becomes `lineMap (y i) (x i) 1 = z` because `c i = 1`. S